{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4d05a9ff-cc38-4ee8-aee6-535eb4901088","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look in these places:\n\n1. **Apple Crash Reports** — macOS automatically generates `.ips` or `.crash` files:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n\n2. **Console.app** — Open it and check **Crash Reports** in the sidebar for a formatted view of the same files.\n\n3. **Core dumps** — macOS disables them by default. To enable:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n   Then reproduce the crash. The core file typically lands in `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n4. **`log show`** — For additional context:\n   ```bash\n   log show --predicate 'eventMessage contains \"your_app_name\"' --last 1h\n   ```\n\n**Tip:** The `.ips` crash report includes the faulting thread's stack trace, signal info, and loaded libraries — often enough to diagnose the issue without a full core dump.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a930486b-394e-4483-afa3-57ba9d9b2793","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT app on macOS when `createdump` isn't available. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":312,"requestId":"609C:1230E4:2D29DA:3AF336:69FFE41D"},"id":"db235fbf-fb9d-414a-b868-728e8d1e1212","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:49:27.460Z","parentId":"7ebef9d9-4fd4-45a7-852a-bf8eb3253232"}
